solution:
Label points $O, N, M$ as follows. [asy]
size(100);

draw( (0,0) -- (8,0) -- (8, 10) -- (0, 10) -- cycle);
dot((8,10)); dot((0,6)); dot((3,10)); dot((8,0));
label("$A$", (8,10) , NE); label("$C$", (0,6), W); label("$B$", (3,10), N); label("$N$", (8,0), SE); label("$O$", (0,0), SW); label("$M$", (0,10), NW); label("5", (1.5, 8), SE);
label(" $8$ ", (0,0)--(8,0), S);

draw((0,0)--(8,0)); draw((0,0)--(0,6)); draw((0,10)--(3,10));
draw((8,0)--(3,10), 1pt+dashed);
draw((0,6)--(3,10)); draw((0,6)--(8,0));
label ("$l$", (6,6), SE);
[/asy] Because folding preserves the corner $A$ (which is now $C$), we have two congruent triangles $\triangle BAN \cong \triangle BCN$.  This means that $AB=BC=5$.  Knowing this, we can compute $MB=8-5=3$ and $MC=\sqrt{5^2-3^2}=4$.

Notice also that we have similar triangles $\triangle BMC \sim \triangle CON$.  (This can be determined by angle chasing.)  Thus, we have $\frac{MB}{CO}=\frac{BC}{CN}=\frac{MC}{ON}=\frac{4}{8}$.  Knowing $MB=3$ and $CB=5$, we can compute $CO=6$ and $CN=10$.

[asy]
size(100);

draw( (0,0) -- (8,0) -- (8, 10) -- (0, 10) -- cycle);
dot((8,10)); dot((0,6)); dot((3,10)); dot((8,0));
label("$A$", (8,10) , NE); label("$C$", (0,6), W); label("$B$", (3,10), N); label("$N$", (8,0), SE); label("$O$", (0,0), SW); label("$M$", (0,10), NW); label("5", (1.5, 8), SE);
label(" $8$ ", (0,0)--(8,0), S);

draw((0,0)--(8,0)); draw((0,0)--(0,6)); draw((0,10)--(3,10));
