question:
Let $ABCD$ be a parallelogram. We have that $M$ is the midpoint of $AB$ and $N$ is the midpoint of $BC.$ The segments $DM$ and $DN$ intersect $AC$ at $P$ and $Q$, respectively. If $AC = 15,$ what is $QA$? [asy]
pair A, B, C, D, pM, pN, O, P, Q;
A = (25, 0) * dir(-20);
B = (15, 0) * dir(60);
C = (25, 0) * dir(160);
D = (15, 0) * dir(-120);
pM = 0.5 * A + 0.5 * B;
pN = 0.5 * B + 0.5 * C;
O = 0.25 * A + 0.25 * B + 0.25 * C + 0.25 * D;
P = 0.33 * C + 0.67 * A;
Q = 0.67 * C + 0.33 * A;
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--C);
draw(pM--D);
draw(pN--D);
label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, NW);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$M$", pM, NE);
label("$N$", pN, NW);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$Q$", Q, NE);
[/asy]

solution:
Solution 1: The segment $BD$ begs to be drawn, so we start there: [asy]
pair A, B, C, D, pM, pN, O, P, Q;
A = (25, 0) * dir(-20);
B = (15, 0) * dir(60);
C = (25, 0) * dir(160);
D = (15, 0) * dir(-120);
pM = 0.5 * A + 0.5 * B;
pN = 0.5 * B + 0.5 * C;
O = 0.25 * A + 0.25 * B + 0.25 * C + 0.25 * D;
P = 0.33 * C + 0.67 * A;
Q = 0.67 * C + 0.33 * A;
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(A--C);
draw(B--D);
draw(pM--D);
draw(pN--D);
label("$A$", A, S);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, NW);
label("$D$", D, S);
label("$M$", pM, NE);
label("$N$", pN, NW);
label("$P$", P, N);
label("$Q$", Q, NE);
[/asy] We can clearly see that now we have triangles $ABD$ and $CBD,$ and $MD,$ $ND,$ and $AC$ are medians to one or more of the triangles. That means that $P$ and $Q$ are the centroids of triangles $ABD$ and $CBD,$ respectively. Since $AC = 15,$ that means $CQ = 5,$ since the median from $C$ to $BD$ is half the length of $AC,$ or $7.5,$ and $CQ$ must be $\frac{2}{3}$ of that, or $5.$ Therefore, $QA = AC - CQ = 15 - 5 = \boxed{10}.$

Solution 2: Since $ABCD$ is a parallelogram, $\overline{AD}$ and $\overline{BC}$ are parallel with $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{DN}$ as transversals.  So $\angle DAQ = \angle NCQ$ and $\angle ADQ = \angle CNQ$, and so $\triangle ADQ$ and $\triangle CNQ$ are similar by AA similarity.

Also, we know opposite sides of a parallelogram are congruent, so $AD = BC$.  Since $N$ is a midpoint of $\overline{BC}$, we have $CN = \dfrac{AD}2$.  By similar triangles, \[ \dfrac{AQ}{CQ} = \dfrac{AD}{CN} = 2, \]so $AQ = 2CQ.$  Since $AQ + CQ = AC = 15$, we have $CQ = 5$ and $AQ = \boxed{10}.$

question:
Circles with centers at $O$ and $P$ have radii 2 and 4, respectively, and are externally tangent. Points $A$ and $B$ on the circle with center $O$ and points  $C$ and $D$ on the circle with center $P$ are such that  $\overline{AD}$ and $\overline{BC}$ are common external tangents to the circles. What is the area of the concave hexagon $AOBCPD$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D,H,O,P;
O = (0,0);
P = (6,0);
H = (-6,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc((A + H)/2, abs(A -  H)/2, 0, 180), arc(O, 2, 0, 180));
D = intersectionpoint(arc((A + P)/2, abs(A -  P)/2, 0, 180), arc(P, 4, 0, 180));
B = reflect(O,P)*(A);
C = reflect(O,P)*(D);
draw(O--P,linewidth(0.7));
draw(Circle(O,2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(Circle(P,4),linewidth(0.7));
draw(interp(A,D,-0.2)--interp(A,D,1.2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(interp(B,C,-0.2)--interp(B,C,1.2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--O--B,linewidth(0.7));
draw(D--P--C,linewidth(0.7));
label("$O$",O,SE);
label("$P$",P,E);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("2",(-0.45,0.95),E);
label("6",(3,0),N);
label("4",(5.55,1.95),E);

[/asy]

solution:
Through $O$ draw a line parallel to $\overline{AD}$ intersecting $\overline{PD}$ at $F$. [asy]
pair A,B,C,D,H,O,P,F;
O = (0,0);
P = (6,0);
H = (-6,0);
A = intersectionpoint(arc((A + H)/2, abs(A -  H)/2, 0, 180), arc(O, 2, 0, 180));
D = intersectionpoint(arc((A + P)/2, abs(A -  P)/2, 0, 180), arc(P, 4, 0, 180));
B = reflect(O,P)*(A);
C = reflect(O,P)*(D);
F=(5.5,1.95);
draw(O--P,linewidth(0.7));
draw(Circle(O,2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(Circle(P,4),linewidth(0.7));
draw(interp(A,D,-0.2)--interp(A,D,1.2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(interp(B,C,-0.2)--interp(B,C,1.2),linewidth(0.7));
draw(A--O--B,linewidth(0.7));
draw(D--P--C,linewidth(0.7));
label("$O$",O,SE);
label("$P$",P,E);
label("$D$",D,NW);
label("$A$",A,NW);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,S);
label("2",(-0.45,0.95),E);
label("6",(3,0),N);
label("$F$",(5.55,1.95),E);
draw(O--F,linewidth(0.7));
label("2",(5.3,2.9),W);
label("2",(5.7,1),W);

[/asy] Then $AOFD$ is a rectangle and $OPF$ is a right triangle. Thus $DF=2$, $FP=2$, and $OF=4\sqrt{2}$. The area of trapezoid $AOPD$ is $12\sqrt{2}$, and the area of hexagon $AOBCPD$ is $2\cdot 12\sqrt{2}=\boxed{24\sqrt{2}}$.

question:
A rectangular piece of paper $ABCD$ is folded so that edge $CD$ lies along edge $AD,$ making a crease $DP.$ It is unfolded, and then folded again so that edge $AB$ lies along edge $AD,$ making a second crease $AQ.$ The two creases meet at $R,$ forming triangles $PQR$ and $ADR$. If $AB=5\mbox{ cm}$ and $AD=8\mbox{ cm},$ what is the area of quadrilateral $DRQC,$ in $\mbox{cm}^2?$

[asy]
size(250);
draw((0,0)--(5,0)--(5,8)--(0,8)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((8,0)--(8,8)--(13,8)--(13,5)--(8,5),black+linewidth(1));
draw((8,0)--(13,5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((16,0)--(21,0)--(21,8)--(16,8)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((16,0)--(21,5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((16,8)--(21,3),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((12,0)--(10,2),black+linewidth(1));
draw((12,0)--(10,2),EndArrow);
label("$A$",(0,8),N);
label("$B$",(5,8),N);
label("$C$",(5,0),S);
label("$D$",(0,0),S);
label("$A$",(8,8),N);
label("$B$",(13,8),N);
label("$C$",(8,5),W);
label("$D$",(8,0),S);
label("$P$",(13,5),E);
label("$A$",(16,8),N);
label("$B$",(21,8),N);
label("$C$",(21,0),S);
label("$D$",(16,0),S);
label("$P$",(21,5),E);
label("$Q$",(21,3),E);
label("$R$",(20,4),W);
